SKILL|python-debugpy|"Debug Python: pdb REPL + debugpy remote (DAP)."
STEP|1|Start with `breakpoint()`.** It's the cheapest thing that works.
STEP|2|A test fails and the traceback doesn't reveal why a value is wrong
STEP|3|You need to step through a function and watch a collection mutate
STEP|4|A long-running process (hermes gateway, tui_gateway) misbehaves and you can't restart it
STEP|5|Post-mortem: an exception fired in prod-ish code and you want to inspect locals at the crash site
STEP|6|A subprocess / child (Python `_SlashWorker`, PTY bridge worker) is the actual bug site
STEP|7|Don't use for:** things `print()` / `logging.debug` solve in under a minute, or things `pytest -vv --tb=long --showlocals` already reveals.
STEP|8|Don't forget to remove `breakpoint()` before committing.** Use `git diff` or a pre-commit grep:
STEP|9|Option 1: `debugpy`'s own CLI REPL** — not an official feature, but a tiny DAP client script:
STEP|10|Option 2: Attach from VS Code / Cursor / Zed** — if the user has one open, they can add a `launch.json`:
STEP|11|Option 3: Ditch DAP, use `remote-pdb`** — usually what you actually want from a terminal agent:
STEP|12|A. Source-edit the gateway:**
STEP|13|B. Use `remote-pdb` at a specific handler:**
STEP|14|**pdb under pytest-xdist silently does nothing.** You won't see the prompt, the test just hangs. Always use `-p no:xdist` or `-n 0`.
STEP|15|**`breakpoint()` in CI / non-TTY contexts hangs the process.** Safe locally; never commit it. Add a pre-commit grep as a safety net.
STEP|16|**`PYTHONBREAKPOINT=0`** disables all `breakpoint()` calls. Check the env if your breakpoint isn't hitting:
STEP|17|**`debugpy.listen` blocks only if you also call `wait_for_client()`.** Without it, execution continues and your first breakpoint may fire before the client is attached.
STEP|18|**Attach to PID fails on hardened kernels.** `ptrace_scope=1` (Ubuntu default) allows only same-user ptrace of child processes. Workaround: `echo 0 > /proc/sys/kernel/yama/ptrace_scope` (needs root) o
STEP|19|**Threads.** `pdb` only debugs the current thread. For multithreaded code, use `debugpy` (thread-aware DAP) or set `threading.settrace()` per thread.
STEP|20|**asyncio.** `pdb` works in coroutines but `await` inside pdb requires Python 3.13+ or `await` from `interact` mode on older versions. For 3.11/3.12, use `asyncio.run_coroutine_threadsafe` tricks or `
STEP|21|**`scripts/run_tests.sh` strips credentials and sets `HOME=<tmpdir>`.** If your bug depends on user config or real API keys, it won't reproduce under the wrapper. Debug with raw `pytest` first to repr
STEP|22|**Forking / multiprocessing.** pdb does not follow forks. Each child needs its own `breakpoint()` or `set_trace()`. For Hermes subagents, debug one process at a time.
STEP|23|[ ] After `pip install debugpy`, confirm: `python -c "import debugpy; print(debugpy.__version__)"`
STEP|24|[ ] For remote debug, confirm the port is actually listening: `ss -tlnp \| grep 5678`
STEP|25|[ ] First breakpoint actually hits (if it doesn't, you likely have `PYTHONBREAKPOINT=0`, you're under xdist, or execution finished before attach)
STEP|26|[ ] `where` / `w` shows the expected call stack
STEP|27|[ ] Post-debug cleanup: no stray `breakpoint()` / `set_trace()` in committed code
STEP|28|"Why is this dict missing a key?"**
STEP|29|"This test passes in isolation but fails in the suite."**
STEP|30|"My async handler deadlocks."**
STEP|31|"Post-mortem on a crash in an Ink child process / subprocess."**
